Commentary.Commentary: We are back. The players are out in the middle. Rohit Sharma and KL Rahul to open for India. Pat Cummins to start with the ball.
...SECOND INNINGS...

Now then, Around 10 overs remaining. India will hope to end the day without losing any wickets. The openers need to give a good start. Australia on the other hand have their skipper as the only seamer. The others need to support him.

India were superb with the ball as well. This pitch has more turn than we saw at Nagpur. The start wasn't that good but they had their moments. Shami started the attack and then Ashwin got two wickets of Marnus Labuschagne and Steven Smith in one over. There was a period where the bowlers looked tired but Shami once again came up with his magic and ended with four wickets. While Ashwin-Jadeja ended with 6 together.

Not quite sure who will be the happier side right now. Of course, Australia would have hoped for more runs but from around 168 for 6, they will take this score. Credit to Handscomb for the way he played. He looked so composed out there. It was very easy for him to bat on while others struggled. His stand with his skipper was very crucial but in the end, Handscomb ran out of partners. Australia were off to a watchful start with Usman Khawaja playing a big role. He scored a brilliant 81 and kept the engine moving while wickets were falling at the other end.

India will take this score as well. Apart from a couple of innings, they are doing well to take wickets at regular intervals. KL Rahul took a stunner to dismiss Khawaja and then India did well to build around it. Now, the final session is coming up. India will look to bundle out Australia under 250 while the tourists will hope this stand flourish more.

A good session for both teams. However, the stand between Peter Handscomb and Pat Cummins has helped Australia to calm things down once again. Australia started the session with Usman Khawaja and Travis Head but the later fell quickly. However, Khawaja and Handscomb played out a superb stand to help get back on track. Khawaja fell after playing a fine innings. Later, there was a flurry of wickets but Cummins has soaked all the pressure.

...Day 1, Session 2...

Australia might have scored bulk of runs but India have the momentum lately. The way Ravichandran Ashwin and Ravindra Jadeja bowled the last few overs, it got really interesting for a while. Before that, Shami was struggling but his second spell was superb and got a wicket as well. Siraj was disciplined as well. The approach by the batters to tackle the spin duo was to unsettle them but Ashwin brought his experience to get rid of the Aussies' wall. A fantastic start to the game. More even than we saw at Nagpur. Let's see how the next session pans out.

A brilliant start to the second match. Australia have scored runs at a good rate but losing Smith and Marnus Labuschagne has worried them a bit. It was a good toss to win at first. Warner and Khawaja were watchful. Khawaja importantly brought all the runs and composure while Warner was struggling. He fell and then Marnus Labuschagne showed some intent but not for long as he and Smith fell in the same over. Travis Head is known to play with a different kind of approach so it will be interesting to see who he bats while Khawaja we feel will play the anchor role throughout.

A short ball on middle, it strucks Khawaja on the pads who goes on the back foot to defend but misses. Could have bounced over but it pitches outside the line.

OUT! EDGED AND GONE! Marnus Labuschagne and Steven Smith in one over. Incredible from Ashwin. What an over and all the hard work throughout the session is getting undone! Smith goes for zero! A rare zero. Ashwin bowls a slower delivery, full and angling across the batter. Smith probably was in two minds, to play or to leave. He does the former half-heartedly. Gets an outside edge and Srikar Bharat takes a low catch behind the stumps.
Commentary.Howout: c Srikar Bharat b Ravichandran Ashwin

INDIA (Playing XI) - Rohit Sharma (C), KL Rahul, Cheteshwar Pujara, Virat Kohli, Shreyas Iyer (In for Suryakumar Yadav), Srikar Bharat (WK), Ravindra Jadeja, Ravichandran Ashwin, Axar Patel, Mohammad Shami, Mohammed Siraj.

Rohit Sharma says batting first would have been ideal but they lost the last toss and played really well after that. Adds they want to play good cricket and not worry much. India on the other hand completely dominated the game but they will expect opposition to come much harder this time. They don't need to tweak much but as it looks like, Iyer might take his place back in the middle order. Interestingly neither team has released their XI unlike every other match. So, stay tuned for toss and other updates.

After a small pause, we welcome back you to the second Test between India and Australia. It was hard for the Aussies to stamp an authority in the first match. They looked completely overshadowed and clueless against the spin web of India. No doubt they were finding it hard and especially their batters but they will hope for much better performance in this second match. The pitch has again been the talking point and let’s see what Delhi has to offer.

The caravan moves to Delhi for the second Test of the Border–Gavaskar Trophy between India and Australia at the Arun Jaitley Stadium. Having emerged victorious in the first Test in Nagpur, India hold a 1-0 lead, and they will be looking to take an unassailable 2-0 lead in this four-match Test series. On the other hand, Australia will be looking to bounce back from a heavy defeat and bring the series back on level terms. In the first Test, after winning the toss, Australia failed to mount a huge score in the first innings and were bundled out for 177. In reply, India's strong batting depth powered them to a first-innings lead of 223 runs. Australia, in their second innings, could not put up any sort of fight and were rolled over for 91, losing by an innings and 132 runs. The visitors cannot afford to carry the baggage from the first Test and need to start afresh if they are to fight their way back in the series. They will be delighted with the return of Mitchell Starc, and Scott Boland is expected to make way for the left-arm pacer. Moreover, Cameron Green is also expected to make the cut, and his inclusion will certainly strengthen their batting, if not the bowling as well. On the other hand, India had a near-perfect game, and they would want to put in a similar performance in the second Test as well. As far as the hosts are concerned, Shreyas Iyer has joined their squad after missing the first Test due to back injury rehab. It will be interesting to see if he is slotted straight back into the playing XI. The form of KL Rahul is a cause of concern for India, and they have the option of replacing him with Shubman Gill. The bowling unit looks settled, and they are likely to stick with the same bowling group. Like the first Test, the second promises to be another exciting encounter between two top teams. Will we see a fightback from Australia, or will India continue their home dominance? We shall find out together.

The Indian top order just did not get going, Kohli and Rohit got off to starts but none went onto make it into something significant. Had it not been for Axar and Ashwin, India would have conceded a big lead to the Aussies. Now this game has become a one-innings shoutout. There are still around overs to go and India will hope they can get a couple at least. Australia on the other hand, will hope they can get through this passage without a lot of damage. An important phase follows.

Before that, it was the Nathan Lyon show on Day 2. He ran through the Indian top order. He was well supported by Todd Murphy and Matthew Kuhnemann. However, they had no answers to the counter-attack by Axar Patel and Ravichandran Ashwin but the second new ball worked really well for them. They have got a lead but it is of just the one run.

So, Australia just manage the lead of 1 run! That is an excellent recovery from the Indians. Australia on the other hand, will be very disappointed. Let me remind you, India were 7 down for 139 but then came a brilliant stand between Axar Patel and Ravichandran Ashwin! The two added over 100 and took India close to Australia's score. Axar Patel was the mainstay and Ashwin played second fiddle. In the end, that stand has changed the look of the game completely.

Another good session for the Aussies but India fought back well at the end of it courtesy Axar Patel and Ravichandran Ashwin! The session began with Jadeja and Kohli looking to get India back on safer shores but the former fell. The latter then followed and Srikar Bharat also did not last for long in the middle. Yet again it was the Aussie spinners who weaved their magic. Nathan Lyon got Srikar Bharat to get his fifer. India were in a lot of trouble with the trail being over 100 and the hosts were 7 down. Axar Patel though has come out all guns blazing and has scored quickly to put a little bit of pressure back on Australia and Ashwin has given him able support. The two need to continue the good work though. Australia on the other hand, will know one wicket and they'll be into the tail. They would be aiming for a lead of over 50. Can they get it?

However, it was India who began the day on the brighter note as Rahul and Rohit seemed at ease but after the introduction of Lyon, things changed, he has all four of the wickets and is looking really threatening. Jadeja and Kohli have started off well and are fighting back but the two need to continue as INdia are still 175 runs behind. Australia on the other hand, need to continue to be patient and disciplined with their lines and lengths. The second session could be a vital one, do join us in a bit.

UPDATE - Australia have a concussion substitue, David Warner who took a few blows on the head while batting has been ruled out of the Test with concussion and it is Matt Renshaw who replaces him.

The Aussies on the other hand, need to strike at regular intervals. There were encouraging sings fir their bowlers in the last session but can they make use of the assistance? Can the Australian bowlers do what the Indians did? The first session is an important one, we will find out...

India continue to dominate in this Test series. Yet again their spinners came to the fore and bowled Austtalia out for an average score and their openers got through the nervy period unscathed. Now the Indians will yet again look to bat long and post a big total.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1 ...
Right then! That concludes Day 1! Day 2 promises to be exciting. Join us back for Day 2 at 0930 IST (0400 GMT) and earlier for the build up. Cheers!

Usman Khawaja is up for a chat. He says the pitch is challenging and it is tough to bat. Adds the game plan is the same, he just tried to bat a bit longer. Applauds the performance of Peter Handscomb for the way he played. He says the wicket slightly suits the right-hander. Hopes the pitch does help them on Day 2.

The spinners took 6 wickets but the seamers extracted more, Shami particularly. He didn't start well but was bang on as he proceeded. India could have kept Australia a bit low but got a bit tired. Still, they have done a commendable job. Too early to call, both teams have done a good job on Day 1. Mohammad Shami claimed 4 wickets while Ashwin-Jadeja ended with 6 together.

Australia won the toss and opted to bat first. They off to a watchful start with Usman Khawaja playing a big role. He played a brilliant innings but got no support from other end. Once Peter Handscomb joined, he took on the baton and he played a wonderful innings to keep the innings on track. There was a handful innings from the skipper as well. All in all, Australia manage to get past 250 which is a really good score on this pitch knowing how it was behaving.

A good day of cricket! a good start to the game! Both teams will be happy with how Day 1 went. India will be happy that they end the day without losing any wickets. It is all even as we conclude Day 1.

... FOURTH INNINGS ...

The pitch is certainly playing tricks. There is spin and variable bounce. Australia have three good spinners in their ranks and they can put up a fight for sure. That said, had they adopted a pragmatic approach with the bat, they had the chance to pressurize the Indian team. Right now, the target won't bother them much. Still, early wickets will throw the cat among the pigeons. We could have a thrilling end to this Test match. Stay tuned...

Mayhem in the morning session! 9 wickets for 53 runs. Australia were demolished by the spin pair of Ravichandran Ashwin and Ravindra Jadeja. The vulnerability of the Aussies against spin was exposed yet again. Their batters kept attempting the sweep shot and kept perishing. Poor technique and execution. They didn't trust their defense and were seen swinging their bat aimlessly. End result, all the advantage gained was lost and now India are 115 away from winning this Test match.

OUT! Bowled! Make it 7 for Jadeja and Australia are all out. Tossed up around off, full in length, Matthew Kuhnemann tries to be fancy with his reverse sweep. Fails to connect cleanly and drags it onto the stumps, off his gloves. Target for India - 115.
Slower and fuller, around off, Murphy defends it off the inner half. Maiden!
Flighted and full, around middle, Todd Murphy drives off the front foot to short cover.
Fuller and outside off, Todd tries to drive but misses.
Loopy and full, around off and turning away, Murphy tries to defend but misses. It goes off his thigh pad to the off side.
Short and on off, Murphy gets back and hits it to point.
Slider around leg, Todd goes back in defense but misses. They appeal but to no avail.
It is quicker and full, on the fourth stump line. Matthew Kuhnemann hangs the blade away from his body. It goes to mid-wicket off the inner half.
Matthew Kuhnemann is the number 11 batter.

OUT! Lyon drags it on and the leg stump goes cartwheeling! Ravindra Jadeja has six wickets now. Gives it some flight and delivers it full and outside off, Nathan Lyon spots the chance to drive through the line but it skids back in to take the inner edge. The ball rockets behind to uproot the leg pole. The procession continues...
It is full, on middle and leg. Lyon tucks it to the leg side. He ventures out looking for a single but is sent back and rightly so. A direct hit could've made things interesting.
Fuller and on off. Nathan Lyon blocks it back to the bowler.
Darted on the pads. Todd Murphy stays inside the crease and clips it past short leg. They cross.
Jadeja serves it full and outside off. Todd Murphy leans forward and defends it out watchfully.
It is full, attacking the pads. Lyon stays back and clips it square on the leg side.
A bit flat and on leg. Todd Murphy prods and works it to the leg side off the outer half. They take a single.
Goes full and on off. Todd Murphy defends it on his front foot.
Flights it up, around middle. Todd Murphy plays it back to the bowler.
Full, once again, around off, coming in with the arm. Todd Murphy lunges forward and remains solid in his defense.
Ashwin goes full and on off. Todd Murphy prods and blocks it into the deck.
This is full, around off. It stays low a bit and turns away sharply. Lyon is unable to put it away.
Flatter and on off. Lyon dabs it out to point.
Tosses it up, full, on middle. Lyon tries to flick it away but it catches the leading edge. The ball lobs towards mid on. Ravindra Jadeja tries to reach it but is met by Todd Murphy on his way.
Nathan Lyon defends this full one back to the bowler.

It is fired in full and on off. Todd Murphy opens the face and taps it towards point. He takes off for a single. Nathan Lyon is quick to react and gets to the other end safely. The throw comes to the keeper who takes the bails off. They appeal, it's referred upstairs but the replays fine Lyon safe.
Todd Murphy is in next.

OUT! LEG STUMP IS PEGGED BACK! Ravindra Jadeja has a fifer. After a brief fightback, Alex Carey departs too. Jadeja delivers it flighted and full, around leg, Alex Carey goes down to play his favourite reverse sweep but picks the wrong line. The ball lands, straightens a hint and goes on to obliterate the leg pole. Australia continue to stare down the barrel. Their shot selection has been exceptionally poor. Lead - 111 runs.
A bit short, outside off. Lyon stays back and slashes it through point. They cross for two runs.

Could have been curtains for Lyon, but he does well to get the jets on. It is flatter and on middle. Alex Carey lunges forward and gets it to the leg side off the outer half. KS Bharat gives it chase, turns and has a shy at the striker's end but misses.
FOUR! Top shot! Ravichandran Ashwin pitches it up. Alex Carey stands tall and lofts it over mid on for a fine boundary.
Goes full, on the pads. Alex Carey nudges it to the leg side.
This is much quicker, in line with the stumps. Alex Carey prods and defends it awkwardly.
Ashwin serves it full and on middle. It is coming in with the arm. Carey gets on his front foot and blocks.
Nathan Lyon prods to this full and blocks it into the deck. A tidy over from Jadeja comes to an end.
It is quicker and fuller, angled into the pads. Lyon goes back and dabs it out.
Full, attacking the stumps. Defended out solidly.
Alex Carey gets low to this full delivery and sweeps it behind square on the leg side. There is protection in the deep. Carey only gets a single here.
It is full and on off. Nathan Lyon knocks it down past the bowler's left. One taken.
Jadeja goes full and on off. Lyon prods and defends it back to the bowler.
Flighted and around off, Alex Carey top-edges his attempted reverse sweep and is lucky that it doesn't carry to backward point. Australia continue to live dangerously.
Skidding down from middle and leg, Carey tries to sweep but misses. A brief appeal from India. Going down.
Fuller and around leg, swept away to deep backward square leg for a single.
FOUR! Australia have taken their lead above 100 now. Tossed up, around middle, Lyon goes down and sweeps it towards fine leg for a boundary.
Loopy again, full and spinning in, Lyon tries to flick but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Loopy and full, around off, Carey reverse-sweeps it to backward point and pinches a single.
Quicker and fuller, around off, Lyon tries to defend but it spins away to beat the bat. A double-wicket maiden for Ravindra Jadeja!
Loopy and around off, Nathan defends it with gentle hands to covers.
Gets on the front foot and defends it to the off side.
Fuller and around off, Lyon is on the front foot as he defends it to the off side.
Who will face the music now? It's Nathan Lyon to deal with the hat-trick delivery.

OUT! BOWLED! A team hat-trick for India and the crowd is going bonkers. Jadeja hurls it across flat and in line with the stumps. Yet another Aussie batter goes down to sweep but it doesn't bounce much and sneaks past the bat. The stumps take a beating and Australia are in deep, deep trouble. Ravindra Jadeja is on a hat-trick.

Drinks break. Australia are staring down the barrel. They were in a good position last evening but failed to drive home the advantage. The Indian spinners have tightened the noose and by picking five wickets this morning, they have forced the touring team on the back foot. Skipper Pat Cummins walks in next.

OUT! CAUGHT! Australia are falling like nine pins. Ravindra Jadeja gets his second wicket of the morning. Dishes out a flighted delivery, full and around off, Peter Handscomb presses forward to drive with firm hands but it spins away and takes a thick outside edge. It flies towards Virat Kohli at first slip who reacts to his left and snaps a sharp catch.
Commentary.Howout: c Virat Kohli b Ravindra Jadeja

Commentary.Commentary: Alex Carey is the new batter.

OUT! LBW! This one looks plumb and the finger has gone up. Peter Handscomb has a word with his partner and advises him to take the referral. Has he got struck outside the line? Let's find out. First, coming to the delivery - It's full and around off, straightening a hint as Matt Renshaw kneels down to sweep. He misses and is pinged on the front pad. DRS time. Nothing on the UltraEdge and the Ball Tracking shows three reds. Ravichandran Ashwin is on a rampage this morning. Sweeping problem for Australia, quips Ravi Shastri on air.
Quicker and on off, Renshaw presses forward and defends it back from the inner half of his blade.
Loopy and around off, Matt skips down the track to flick but misses. He is hit on the pads and another muted appeal for an lbw follows.
What a delivery! Drifting in around off, Matt Renshaw tries to play the line but it spins away to beat the outside edge.
Shout for an lbw! The finger stays down. Flatter and fuller, around leg and skidding down, Renshaw fails to defend and is rapped on the pads. Ashwin feels it's going down and hence no review.
Sharp turn and bounce. Flighted and outside off, Matt Renshaw leaves it alone. A good take by Srikar Bharat.
Quicker one, full and on off, Handscomb gets on the front foot in defense. End of a successful over by Jadeja.
Flighted and full, Peter Handscomb defends it past silly point.
Peter Handscomb is the new man at the crease.

OUT! SOUND OF TIMBER! The crowd roars and Marnus Labuschagne is out of here. He did the cardinal mistake of assuming that just because the ball is flat, it will be short. Jadeja serves it around off and it skids in along with staying low. Marnus Labuschagne goes deep inside the crease, trying to keep it out but it perhaps brushes the bottom edge and goes behind to rattle the stumps. Marnus returns with a dejected look. India have wrestled back the momentum. Australia are 96 runs ahead with 6 wickets in hand.
Slower through the air, around off and turning away, Marnus Labuschagne stays back and pushes it with an angled bat to point.
Risky from Renshaw. Fuller and around leg, Matt Renshaw brings out the reverse sweep. Doesn't connect well but it goes towards short third man. They cross.
Very full and around leg, it's eased towards mid-wicket for a single.

Nearly a catch at short leg. Flighted and on middle, turning in, Marnus Labuschagne flicks and it goes through the legs of Shreyas Iyer for a run. That was definitely an opportunity but Shreyas was late in his reflexes.
Tossed up, full and outside off, Marnus skips down the track and defends it to the off side.

Fuller and around leg, Matt Renshaw goes down and sweeps it towards short fine leg. They appeal but nothing from the umpire as the batters cross. India don't review and it's a given as a run. Renshaw is off the mark.
Drifting down the leg side, Marnus Labuschagne goes back and works it behind square leg for a single.

Ravichandran Ashwin pulls out once again. Second time this morning. The crowd is behind Ashwin here. They are here to see some historic moment, one that would stay in their memories for a longer time.
Extra loop on this one, full and outside off, Marnus tries to push at it but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Floated delivery, full and on off, Marnus lunges and defends it to short mid-wicket.
A bit flat and around off. Marnus Labuschagne stays back and cuts it to point. He takes off and gets to the other end safely.
This is full and on off, coming in with the arm. Marnus Labuschagne knocks it out to cover.
Flatter and fuller, blocked off the front foot to covers.
Too full and straight, Marnus works it through mid-wicket for two runs.
Fuller and around off, defended off the front foot.
Tossed up outside off, Marnus drives it to the right of sweeper cover and comes back for the second run.
Matt Renshaw is the new batter. He's the concussion substitute for David Warner.

OUT! LBW! Ravichandran Ashwin and company make a loud appeal for lbw, they think that they have got their man here. The umpire thinks the same and raises his dreaded finger. Steven Smith though has a chat with his partner and takes the review. Coming to the delivery - It is tossed up, full and around off. The ball stays low off the deck and spins in as well. Smith gets low and tries to sweep it away but does not get any bat on the ball. The ball goes through to ping him on the pads. DRS time. The UltraEdge shows no bat is involved. The Ball Tracking later confirms that it is the umpire's call on the ball hitting the wickets. Australia do not lose a review here but they lose Smith cheaply.

Steven Smith has been adjudged lbw. A big moment in this Test match. Smith has a word with Marnus Labuschagne and takes the referral. This one looked out to the naked eye. Let's find out. UltraEdge is taking ages to load. Everyone is waiting. Here it comes... no spike, a bit of daylight. Ball Tracking comes and it shows that the ball is clipping the leg stump, it's the umpire's call and India have two in the morning session already. The crowd is jubilant.
Goes full again, outside off this time. Marnus Labuschagne pushes it gently towards covers and gets to the other end.
Loops it up, full, on off. Marnus Labuschagne defends it watchfully off the front foot.
It is full, on off. It skids through. Marnus Labuschagne gets his blade down in time to jam it out.
Marnus Labuschagne gets on his front foot to defend this full one.
This is floated and full, around middle and leg. It stays a touch low off the deck. Marnus Labuschagne uses the depth of his crease and nudges it to the leg side.
A bit flatter and on off. Smith goes back and taps it out towards point. Jadeja running through his overs here, as always.
Tosses it up, full and outside off. Smith steps across and drives it towards sweeper cover. The batters take a couple this time.
Drifts in, full and around the fourth stump. It grips and turns away sharply. Smith lets it be.
FOUR! Lovely footwork and Smudge gets his first boundary. Flatter and fuller, around middle, Steven Smith walks down the track and lofts it over wide mid on for a boundary.
Shortish and on off, Smith goes back and plays it down to point.
Flighted and full, around off, Smith steps out to drive but slices it towards point.

NOT OUT! Marnus Labuschagne celebrates instantly as he sees that the impact is outside the line. A small victory for him in this morning session. Ravichandran Ashwin goes full and outside off. The ball grips and turns in. Marnus Labuschagne gets down on one knee and tries to sweep it away. He fails to connect and takes a blow on his pads. Ashwin appeals but the finger stays down. Rohit has a word with Bharat and Ashwin before taking the referral. Nothing on the UltraEdge and later, the Ball Tracking confirms that the impact is outside off.

Yet another shout for an lbw. The finger has stayed down. Rohit Sharma comes rushing to his keeper, has a word with him and the bowler. He takes the referral on this occasion. The impact is outside off.

A loud appeal for lbw! It is tossed up, around off. Marnus Labuschagne gets low and tries to sweep it away. He misses and takes a hit on the pads. Ashwin and company appeal but the umpire is unmoved. Spinning too much, perhaps.
Marnus Labuschagne steps out of the crease this time and defends this full one out solidly.
FOUR! The reverse comes out now. Marnus Labuschagne strides forward to this full one. He is in full control of the reverse sweep and finds the boundary at deep backward point.
Use of the feet straight away after the last ball. Smith jumps down the track to a full ball around off and knocks it down to long on for a single.
Lovely delivery! This is quicker, angled across the right-hander. Smith is caught in two minds - in the end, he does not go through with his shot as he hangs deep inside the crease.
Excellent over from Jadeja comes to an end. Just a single off this one. This time Jadeja targets the pads. Marnus Labuschagne stays inside the crease. He tucks it towards backward square leg.
Loopy ball, around off, a touch fuller. Marnus Labuschagne defends it watchfully.
Short one, on off. Marnus Labuschagne makes some room and helps it out to point.
A bit flatter, on off. Smith goes on his back foot and punches it to covers for a single.
Two dots to start with now. It is floated and full, outside off. It grips and turns further away. Smith has no interest in playing away from his body.
A dot to start with! Jadeja goes full and outside off. Smith leans in and drives it to covers.
Beaten! This one scoots past the edge. Full and outside off, skidding away, Marnus is forward in defense but misses. A similar delivery got Smith in the first inning.
FOUR! Well played! Loopy and full, around middle, Marnus Labuschagne goes down on one knee and calmly paddles it to fine leg for a boundary.

Oh, hello! Ravichandran Ashwin stops in his delivery stride and the crowd gets excited. Ashwin and Mankading - a story in itself. Steven Smith is only left with a grim smile on his face as he stays inside the crease.
Fullish and on middle, Smith works it gently to the right side of the mid-wicket fielder for a single. Opens his account.
Slower through the air, full and around off, Smith defends it back off the front foot.
A touch short and around off, Smith goes on the back foot and defends it to the off side.
Ashwin comes from 'round the wicket to Marnus Labuschagne. Serves it full and around leg, Marnus steps down and wrists it through mid-wicket for a single.
Loopy and full, around middle and off, Smith takes his front leg forward as he drives it to covers, again.
Flatter this time, a touch short and on off, turning away, Smith punches from the back foot to covers.
Short this time, outside off, Smith cuts with the spin but finds point.
Flighted and full, around off, Smith allows the ball to come to him and blocks it to covers.
Fuller and outside off, Marnus strides forward and strokes it through covers for a single.
Jadeja starts with a full ball outside off, Marnus Labuschagne is on the front foot as he pushes it to covers.
Early breakthrough for India. Now, Steven Smith comes out at number 4. Also, it will be Ravindra Jadeja to bowl from the other end.

OUT! Head is gone, caught behind! Smart bowling from Ashwin. He keeps bowling in the region around off and gets the ball to skid into the batter. This time there is some extra toss and as a result, there is some extra bite from the surface. Loopy and full, drifting in around off, Travis Head commits himself forward in defense but it spins away to take the outside edge. Srikar Bharat stays low and takes a fine catch. He takes the bails off as well. The finger though is up after the appeal for a caught behind and Head departs after a promising knock. Australia lead by 66 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Srikar Bharat b Ravichandran Ashwin

Commentary.Commentary: A touch flatter and quicker, around off, Head defends it close to his front pad.
Floated one, full and around off, Tavis drives it back to the bowler.
FOUR! Australia are away on Day 3. Too full from Ashwin, outside off, Head gets on the front foot and drills his drive through covers for a boundary.
Presses forward to a full ball and pushes it gently to short cover.
Ashwin begins with a fuller ball around middle, Head is on the front foot as he defends it back.

The morning session of a moving day is set to begin. The Indian players make their way out on the field. Followed by Travis Head and Marnus Labuschagne who walk out to continue with their innings. Both the teams will look to get off to a good start here. It will be Ravichandran Ashwin to start the proceedings with the ball.

PITCH REPORT - Sanjay Manjrekar is near the playing area. He starts by saying there are no dramatic changes to the deck on Day 3 from Day 2. Matthew Hayden joins and says that the conditions are a bit cooler and the pitch with black soil has started to deteriorate. He spots big cracks and tells us that he has never seen such big ones before. The Aussie points out the good-length area for a right-arm fast bowler coming around the wicket for a left-hander and opines that could be a concern. Feels that Australia are looking to score quickly because of this very reason.

With no David Warner available after suffering a concussion and a hairline fracture, Travis Head got the opportunity to open the innings and the southpaw has shown a lot of intent despite losing Usman Khawaja early. The morning session today is all about driving the advantage home. Let's see whether Australia extend their upper hand or India manage to claw back. Should be an entertaining morning and day.

The play on Day 2 was all about collapse and recovery. India threw away a decent start by losing wickets in a heap only to recover with a partnership between Kohli and Jadeja. A contentious decision against Virat led to another collapse and then Axar and Ashwin combined to put India on an even keel against Australia with a wonderful century association.

Let's roll! We head into the 'moving day' of the Kotla Test match and against all the odds, Australia find themselves closest to the driver's seat. Day 2 was action-packed, to say the least, and we are expecting more of the same to continue. The touring team has its nose in front but we've seen momentum changing quite quickly in this Test and not one team has managed to keep it on its side for a longer period. We will wait and watch which way the pendulum swings on Day 3. On that note, allow us to welcome you to the coverage. Stay tuned for more...
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

Now Australia will hope these two who have got their eye in put up a good stand, Australia will love a score of above 250 and we can surely see them play with intent on Day 3 as well. India on the other hand, are slightly on the back foot at the moment but we have seen on this wicket a collapse can always be around the corner and Rohit will hope that is the case. A very exciting Day 3 awaits. Do join us at 0930 IST (0400 GMT). The build up begins a lot earlier. Till then, take care and goodbye!

Earlier in the day, Australia had India on the back foot when Lyon ran through the top order. India were around 140 for 7 but Axar Patel came to the rescue along with Ashwin and the two ensured Australia get the smallest of leads. In reply, with a lead of one, Australia have begun well.

Australia will be very pleased with the 12 overs they faced at the end of Day 2! Yes, they lost Khawaja early but then Head and Marnus Labuschagne played really well. Especially the former who took the attack to the bowlers. and Australia are in a reall good position at the moment. For India, Jadeja got the only breakthrough but Shami and Ashwin were not at their best, especially the latter, he was a little too full in this session and Rohit will be disappointed more with the rate Australia scored at.
On the stumps, blocked. THAT WILL BE STUMPS ON DAY 2!
Flatter and on middle, defended.
On middle, this is flicked through mid-wicket for one.
On middle, this is nudged on the leg side.
On off, this is pushed to mid off.
Fuller and on off, this is pushed through covers for one.
Just wide! Marnus Labuschagne steps out, he flicks uppishly but wide of mid-wicket for one.
On the stumps, this is nudged to mid-wicket.
On middle, this is flicked to mid-wicket.
Outside off, this is uppishly but just wide of silly mid off for one down to long off.
SIX! A full toss, Head feasts on it. He hits it over the long on fence for a biggie.
On middle, kept out.
On middle, kept out.
On middle, kept out.
Flatter and on off, this is guided to point.
On middle, this is worked through square leg for one.
FOUR! Hammered! This is tossed up outside off, it is hit through covers and this one races away to the fence.
On the pads, Head looks to flick but it goes off the glove towards short leg. Head did well to take one hand off the handle and keep it down.
Another run as this is worked through mid-wicket.
On the stumps, defended.
Angled into the pads, this is worked through mid-wicket for one.
On middle, blocked.
On off, this is hit down to long off for one.
On middle, blocked.
FOUR! Two in a row and third in the over. Another sweep shot which is played really well. It is hit through square leg for a boundary.
FOUR! Swept and swept hard again! On middle, this is hit through square leg for a boundary.
On middle, kept out.
FOUR! Hit hard! On middle, fuller, Marnus Labuschagne goes down on one knee and sweeps it wide of mid-wicket for a boundary.
On middle, this is flicked to mid-wicket.
A single as this is worked through square leg.
BEATEN! This is angled across the off pole. Marnus Labuschagne looks to defend but is beaten.
Steps out and hits it down to long off for one.
On middle, defended.
FOUR! That is a lovely shot! Travis Head steps out and strokes it through covers for a boundary.
A single as this is worked through mid-wicket for one.
A single as this is pushed wide of mid off.
On middle, defended.

OUT! TAKEN! That is great anticipation from Iyer and Jadeja strikes in his first over. Usman Khawaja falls! He goes down on one knee to play the paddle scoop but Iyer moves to his left seeing that. Khawaja connects but Iyer latches onto it. Really good.
Commentary.Howout: c Shreyas Iyer b Ravindra Jadeja

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Rahul just did not pick that one. On middle, Usman Khawaja heaves it over the mid-wicket fielder and into the fence.
A single as this is pushed wide of mid off.
On middle, defended.
On off, defended.
A single now as this is pushed through covers.
FOUR! Head dealing in boundaries! On the pads, this is worked through square leg for a boundary.
On middle, kept out.
On off, kept out.
BEATEN! This lands around off, it pitches and then turns away. Head is beaten.
A single as this is pushed through covers.
On middle, this is defended.
Around off, this is pushed to cover.
On middle, blocked.
FOUR! Timed nicely! Outside off, Head leans into the stroke and hits it through covers. He has started well.
Good length and on off, kept out.
FOUR! Top, top shot! Not that short, on middle, Head rocks back and pulls it through mid-wicket and this one races awya to the fence.
On off, defended. A maiden by Khawaja.
Flatter and on off, this is pushed to cover.
Really well bowled! Watching the batter till the end. Usman Khawaja steps out but the length is shortened. Usman Khawaja looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
Flatter and on middle, Khawaja yet again goes back and defends.
Very full and on middle, this is pushed to cover.
Usman Khawaja steps out but the length is shortened. It is defended.
Good length and on off, Head pushes it to mid off.
Good length and on off, this is pushed to cover.
Back of a length and on off, Head pushes it to mid off.
Two more! Around off, this is guided through point for two.
That is a beauty! Length and on off, it comes in with the angle, lands and then moves away. Head is beaten as he tries to defend.
Well wide outside off, left alone.
Good stop by Kohli! Down the leg side. Usman Khawaja looks to flick but misses. It hits the pad of Srikar Bharat and Kohli then dives to his right and stops it.
Really full this time, Khawaja blocks.
Tossed up on middle, Usman Khawaja stays back and defends.
Head is underway too! On middle, this is nudged through mid-wicket for one more.
Floats it up on off, Head defends.
Angled into the pads, this is worked through mid-wicket for one. Usman Khawaja and Australia are underway!

Right then. That's it from the coverage of this match and India have taken an unassailable lead in the series. The Aussies will be ruing an opportunity they missed to win this game and level the series. There are two more Test matches left and we now move to Indore for the third Test match at the Holkar Cricket Stadium. The match is scheduled to begin on Wednesday 1st March and the first ball will be at 9.30 am IST (4 am GMT) but as you all know you can join us early for the build-up. Until then, take care and goodbye!

Ravindra Jadeja wins the PLAYER OF THE MATCH award for his exceptional spin bowling as he claims a 10-wicket match haul and his useful 26 runs in the first innings. He starts by saying that he was enjoying his bowling. He kept attacking the stumps and knew that the batter will stick to sweep or reverse sweep. Mentions their intent was very aggressive as they were looking to get quick runs. Ends by saying that no one can play sweep shots against him, at least on such wickets.

Rohit Sharma the skipper of India says it is a fantastic result for them. Adds that it is remarkable how things were looking at one stage and how they finished their job, especially the bowlers. Claims that even though they were just one run off the Australian score, they were still behind in the game as they had to bat last. Mentions that taking nine wickets in the first session was a fantastic effort and they did well to finish the game with the bat as well. When asked about the Australian's shot selection he says that on a pitch like this, they need to be prepared to do different things, but the opponents were not used to these conditions so it is tough. Admits that they were waiting for the mistakes to happen and they had discussed plans which worked for them. Tells that in every game that is played in this weather, there is some moisture in the wicket so there is a lot to offer in the first session and soon the pitch starts to deteriorate. Goes on to say that they wanted to keep it tight and stay disciplined with the spinners at his disposal masters of this condition. Adds that they know what to do so they needed to stay calm. Ends by saying that when you play Test cricket there are a lot of moments to look back at but the key moments were the partnerships between Virat Kohli and n Ravindra Jadeja as well as Ravindra Jadeja and Axar Patel as getting a 100-run partnership on this wicket is never easy.

Pat Cummins the captain of Australia is in for a chat. He starts by saying that the guys bounced back really well. Informs that India batted really well and the match was in the balance at the innings break. Mentions that the pressure was on India when they got around 280 or whatever it was in the first innings, but they could not make the most of it. Informs they will work on their shot selection and the approach in the coming matches. Adds that they missed a good chance to come out on top in this match. Also says that you can never let an opportunity slip out of your hands while playing in India.
Time for the presentation...

Cheteshwar Pujara is up for a chat and he says that it has been a great Test match. Adds that it is a really special feeling especially to get the winning runs. He congratulates the guys from Saurashtra for winning the Ranji Trophy. Tells that he thought they might've to chase something around 250 runs and they were well prepared for it. Informs that they were disappointed with the way they leaked runs in the last session on Day 2 but are happy with the way the bowlers turned up. Says that it is better to use your feet on a turning track and that's what he focused on. Mentions that it is difficult in the initial phase when you walk in with the blade, but once you play 30-40 balls it becomes easier to score.

Having bowled Australia all out on Day 1, India did well to go into Stumps unscathed and came into Day 2 looking to be positive but had a dismal first session as they lost 4 wickets for 20 runs with Nathan Lyon wreaking havoc. They soon found themselves seven down with 139 runs on the board and it looked like Australia would come out to bat with a lead of close to 100. Axar Patel and Ravichandran Ashwin defied all odds and added a 114-runs for the eighth wicket which helped India cut down the deficit drastically. Axar Patel scored a match-saving knock of 74 runs in 115 balls with Ravichandran Ashwin supporting him with a well-made 31. Nathan Lyon continued to ply his trade effectively and became the third bowler to take 100 Test wickets against India en route to his five-wicket haul. The other two spinners Matthew Kuhnemann and Todd Murphy claimed two wickets each with the skipper Pat Cummins taking one wicket. India trailed by one run and Australia began their second essay with Travis Head looking to play his shots. Ravindra Jadeja dismissed Usman Khawaja but Marnus Labuschagne combined with Travis Head to add 61 runs in 12 overs.

Australia won the toss once again and opted to bat first which seemed to work wonderfully for them as they started off with a 50-run opening partnership between David Warner and Usman Khawaja. David Warner's poor series continued as he was dismissed by Mohammad Shami and to make matters worse he fractured his arm which ruled him out of the Test match. Since he had taken a blow on his head as well, Matt Renshaw replaced him as a concussion substitute. Ravichandran Ashwin turned the tie slightly in India's favor as he claimed the wickets of Marnus Labuschagne and Steven Smith in the same over but Usman Khawaja went on to score 81 runs in 125 balls. Several batters got decent starts but could not make the most of it on a difficult pitch and it was the partnership between Peter Handscomb and Pat Cummins that pushed them to a competitive first-inning score with the former remaining unbeaten on 72. Mohammad Shami claimed 4 wickets as he was able to reverse swing the ball with Ravindra Jadeja and Ravichandran Ashwin contributing with three each.

The day started with Australia in front of the game as they had a lead of 62 runs and nine wickets in hand to build a formidable target. With India batting in the fourth inning, any target near 200 would have been challenging for the home side to chase down. Travis Head had gotten the visitors off to a flying start but was dismissed in the first over with Ravindra Jadeja finding the outside edge of the bat. Steven Smith joined his favorite batting partner Marnus Labuschagne out in the middle and India would have felt that this partnership could easily take the game away from them. However, Ravichandran Ashwin who has done this numerous times in his career opened the floodgates by dismissing Steven Smith and his partner in crime Ravindra Jadeja sent Marnus Labuschagne packing. Australia collapsed from 85 for the loss of two wickets to being bowled out for 113 having scored 28 runs for the loss of 8 wickets. Ravindra Jadeja was the destroyer-in-chief as he claimed 7 wickets and Ravichandran Ashwin chipped in with three crucial wickets. India did have a stumble just before Lunch as KL Rahul was dismissed by Nathan Lyon giving the visitors some hope.

India walked out for the Post-Lunch session requiring 101 runs with nine wickets in hand and Rohit Sharma was in no mood to take his time accumulating the runs out in the middle. He began his onslaught using his feet right from the start and scored 31 in 20 balls before some miscommunication with Cheteshwar Pujara resulted in him getting run out. Virat Kohli came to the wicket looking to be positive but was deceived by Todd Murphy after getting off to a start and was stumped for the first time in his career. Shreyas Iyer came out and played a couple of good shots to not allow the pressure of wickets to get on the team but holed out into the deep off the bowling of Nathan Lyon. Cheteshwar Pujara by then had adopted the anchor role as he secured one end and he was joined by Srikar Bharat who played a few cracking strokes to help India get over the finish line.

INDIA HAVE A 2-0 LEAD IN THE SERIES! They have managed to retain the Border-Gavaskar Trophy and are one step closer to booking their spot for the final of the World Test Championship. This has been an absolute tug-a-war between two competitive sides who love to win and it is the home side that has emerged victorious by 6 wickets in a low-scoring affair. Day 3 has been owned by the bowlers and the moving day of Test cricket moved so fast that the game was completed in two sessions.

FOUR! Cheteshwar Pujara finishes things off in style. He racks up the winning runs in his 100th Test match. What a moment for the veteran. It is pitched up, around middle and leg. Cheteshwar Pujara dances down the track and flicks it over mid on. The ball races away to the fence. India win the match by 6 wickets.
This is flatter and wide outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara shuffles way across and bodies it away.
Full and on leg. Pujara blocks it to short mid-wicket.
It is tossed up, full and on middle. Pujara comes down the wicket and tucks it to the leg side for no run.
Srikar Bharat is unable to end the game in this over! It is spilled way down the leg side. Bharat lets it be.
Full, outside off. Pujara shuffles across and clips it square on the leg side for one more. Scores level now!
Floats it up, full and on middle. Srikar Bharat uses his feet and flicks it down to wide long on for a single.
SIX! BANG! Srikar Bharat is in some hurry. It is full and outside off. Srikar Bharat gets down on one knee and slogs it over the deep mid-wicket fence. Incredible strike.
Flatter, on middle and leg. Cheteshwar Pujara flicks it off his pads to deep square leg and crosses.
Looped up, outside off, turns in off the deck. Pujara clips it to square leg.
FOUR! Incredible shot. Bharat is acing his cover drives here. This is pitched up, on fourth stump. Srikar Bharat creams it through the cover region. The ball has enough legs to reach the fence.
Floats it up, on off. Bharat blocks it away.
Tight leave! Flatter and in the channel. Srikar Bharat shoulders his arms at it.
This is full, on middle, coming in with the arm. Bharat dabs it out to the off side.
FOUR! 14 runs needed to win now. It is tossed up, outside off. Bharat comes down the track and drives it through the cover region for four runs.
Goes full and on off. Bharat steps across and defends it out to point.
Short one, on leg. Bharat swivels and flicks it to deep square leg for a single.
Goes full and on fourth stump. Bharat lunges and pushes it gently to mid off.
Flatter and on leg. Srikar Bharat nudges it to the leg side.
Fuller, on middle and leg. Srikar Bharat gets forward and gets an inside edge on his pads.
FOUR! Exquisite shot! It is tossed up, wide outside off. Srikar Bharat leans in and creams it through covers for four runs.
Floated and full, wide of off. Cheteshwar Pujara shuffles and taps it to point. They take a single.
Srikar Bharat presses forward to this full ball and defends it into the deck.
Flatter and on leg. Srikar Bharat stays back and flicks it through mid-wicket. Two runs taken.
Full, on fifth stump. Bharat dabs it out.
Three dots to start with! This is outside off. Srikar Bharat prods and shuffles across.
Full again, comes in with the arm. Srikar Bharat presses forward and defends it out.
Floats it in, full and on off. Bharat defends it to cover.
Matthew Kuhnemann (5-0-28-0) comes back into the attack.
Fuller, on fifth stump. Bharat steps across and blocks it to the off side. He gets across to the other and gets off the mark as well.
Full and on fourth stump. Bharat prods and blocks it out.
Srikar Bharat has been sent above Ravindra Jadeja with India turning to him to wrap up this run chase.

OUT! CAUGHT! Shreyas Iyer holes out hunting for another biggie. There is still hope for the Aussies. It is full and on off. It turns in a touch. Shreyas Iyer dances down the track and heaves it across the line to deep mid-wicket. Everyone thought that this one will cross the fence as well. Although, Iyer does not get enough distance on it. Todd Murphy takes a sharp catch in the deep.
Commentary.Howout: c Todd Murphy b Nathan Lyon

Commentary.Commentary: Very full, on off. Cheteshwar Pujara drills it down to long on for a single.
Cheteshwar Pujara uses his feet once again. He pads this full ball away from outside off.
Fuller, outside off, turning in late. Cheteshwar Pujara comes across and defends it to point.
SIX! Oof! This is a shot and a half. Murphy serves it full and on middle. Shreyas Iyer dances down the track and smokes it over the long on fence for a biggie.
On the pads, nudged to short mid-wicket.
Murphy goes full and on middle. Cheteshwar Pujara leans forward and flicks it past mid on for one.
FOUR! Smacked! Short one, in the channel. Cheteshwar Pujara goes back and crunches it through covers. Boundary. Exceptionally played.
Much quicker, outside off, angling away. Cheteshwar Pujara steps across but misses to block it away.
Flatter and on off. Pujara stays back and punches it to mid off.
Looped up delivery bowled full and outside off. Shreyas Iyer gets well forward to defend and gets hit on his pads. Another appeal but the umpire remains unmoved.
Bowls this slightly short and into the pads once again. Shreyas Iyer tucks this towards short fine leg.
Gets this to spin into the pads from outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara walks across the stumps and flicks the ball to square leg for one.
Loopy delivery bowled full and on a leg stumps line. Shreyas Iyer charges down the wicket and clips this towards deep square leg for one.
FOUR! Great use of the crease! Nathan Lyon bowls this slightly short and just outside the off stump, Shreyas Iyer goes really deep in the crease and cuts this towards deep point for four runs.
Nathan Lyon tosses this one full and in line with the stumps, Shreyas Iyer shimmies forward and dabs this back to the bowler.
Loopy delivery bowled full and outside the off pole. Cheteshwar Pujara dabs this towards point to end a successful over for Australia.

Bowls this one slightly short and outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara dabs this to the right of the slip fielder who grabs hold of the ball and throws it at the stumps. Cheteshwar Pujara has to rush back into the crease.
Tosses this one full and just outside off. Shreyas Iyer eases this down to long on for a single and will open his account.
Flights this one full and outside off. Shreyas Iyer strokes this to the right of the cover fielder who makes a good stop.

Drinks break! Todd Murphy strikes and gets rid of Virat Kohli who was looking to be in good touch. Australia still need 7 wickets to win the match. Keeping in the mind the depth of the Indian batting order, only a miracle can get the Aussies across the line here. Will they be able to force a collapse? Let's find out. Meanwhile, Shreyas Iyer walks out at number 5 for India. 46 needed to get over the line.

OUT! STUMPED! Todd Murphy has been rewarded for some really good bowling in his last few overs! He gets the big wicket of Virat Kohli and Australia are keeping themselves in contention on a tricky surface. Todd Murphy flights this one full and outside the off stump, another delivery that goes through with the arm after pitching. Virat Kohli looks to take a couple of steps down the wicket to negate the turn but gets beaten on the outside edge. Alex Carey makes no mistake collecting the ball and whipping the bails off with the batter stranded well outside the crease. Virat Kohli has been stumed for the first time in his career as India lose their third wicket and they need to be a bit careful here.
Commentary.Howout: st Alex Carey b Todd Murphy

Commentary.Commentary: Todd Murphy fires this one through on a fuller length and outside off. Virat Kohli looks to defend and gets beaten.

Loopy delivery bowled full and outside off Cheteshwar Pujara gets his pads forward first and hides his bat behind it. The ball raps the pads and there is an appeal. Pat Cummins is enquiring with the umpire if the batter offered a shot as the impact was cleary outside off.
A tad bit shorted and outside the off pole. Cheteshwar Pujara transfers his weight on the back foot and punches this towards mid on.
Flights this one full and wide outside off, going straight through. Cheteshwar Pujara gets his pads well forward and leaves the ball.
Tosses this one full and in line with the stumps. Cheteshwar Pujara shuffles down the wicket and clips this to short mid-wicket.
Full once again and on an off stump line. Cheteshwar Pujara stays in the crease and knocks this back towards the bowler.
Nathan Lyon floats this one full and outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara shimmies down the wicket and blocks this ball towards mid off.
Loops this one full and outside off. Virat Kohli taps this towards the fielder at short mid-wicket. Todd Murphy is keeping it tight here with another maiden!
Beaten once again! Todd Murphy bowls another straighter one on a fuller length and outside the off stump. Virat Kohli looks to block but misses.
Tosses this one full and outside off. Virat Kohli uses his wrists and flicks this towards mid-wicket.
Floats this one full and going towards the off side with the arm. Virat Kohli pushes at the ball and gets beaten on the outside edge.
Delivers this one slightly short and outside the off stump. Virat Kohli gets across the stumps and dabs this towards short leg.
Todd Murphy bowls full and just outside off. Virat Kohli gets well forward and knocks this back to the bowler.
Attacks the pads once again on a shorter length. Virat Kohli whips this towards deep mid-wicket for a single and will retain strike.
Continues to bowl on a shortish length and pitching outside leg. Virat Kohli turns this to the right of backward square leg.

FOUR! What a remarkable shot as the ball just races away to the fence! Nathan Lyon bowls this short as well and on the pads. Virat Kohli finds the gap at backward square leg to perfection and collects four runs.
Back to bowling short and in line with the stumps, Virat Kohli goes on the back foot and dabs this towards short leg.
Floats this one full and outside the off stump. Virat Kohli gets on the front foot and pushes the ball towards cover.
Nathan Lyon bowls this one slightly short and outside off. Virat Kohli goes deep in the crease and blocks this back down the pitch towards the bowler.
Attacks the stumps on a shorter length. Cheteshwar Pujara dabs this towards short leg. A maiden over for Todd Murphy.
Tosses this one full and in line with the stumps, Cheteshwar Pujara flicks this towards square leg.
Continues to bowl short and on the pads. Cheteshwar Pujara cant find the gap on the leg side.
Slightly short and pitching outside leg. Cheteshwar Pujara rocks back and clips this towards mid-wicket.
Floats this one full and on a leg stump line. Cheteshwar Pujara tucks this to the left of short fine leg.
Todd Murphy bowls this short and going down leg. Cheteshwar Pujara misses out as he pulls this straight to short fine leg.
FOUR! Too easy for Kohli! It is flatter, down leg. Kohli goes back and glances it around the corner. The ball races away to the fine leg fence. India 51 runs away from the win.
Floated, sliding down leg. Puraja stays back and tickles it down to fine leg. One taken.
Cheteshwar Pujara charges down the wicket and smacks it to mid off. Unfortunte to not find the gap here.
Much fuller, attacking the stumps. Pujara uses the crease well to defend it out.
Lyon serves it full, on leg. Cheteshwar Pujara hangs back to clip it to the leg side.
Flatter, on off. Pujara steps down and defends it out off the inner half.
Goes full and on off. Kohli defends it out solidly.

A loud appeal for caught behind but the umpire is unmoved. It is tossed up, on off. It grips and turns away a touch. Kohli tries to defend it on his front foot but misses. The ball zips past the outside edge. Todd Murphy thinks he got some wood on it but he is unable to convince his skipper for the review.
Tosses it up, on middle and leg. Kohli tucks it to short leg.
Flatter, on leg stump. Kohli lunges forward and blocks it away.
Full, around middle and leg. Cheteshwar Pujara flicks it through mid-wicket for a single.
Goes full and on off, angling across. Cheteshwar Pujara presses forward and tries to defend it inside the line. The ball catches the outside edge and runs down to third man. They take two here.
Loops it up, around leg. Virat Kohli uses the depth of crease to flick it away but ends up playing all around it. He wears it on the pads, but the impact is down leg.
On off, pushed gently to mid off by Pujara to rotate the strike.
Darted on the pads, Cheteshwar Pujara flicks it in front of square on the leg side
Fuller and on leg. Virat Kohli nudges it to square leg and takes a single.
On off,defended out.

FOUR! The Kohli chants go on and on. He gets his first boundary of the chase. It is full and on off. Virat Kohli gets to the pitch of it and lofts it over the bowler's head for four runs. Virat Kohli becomes the fastest batter to get to 25000 International runs across all formats.
Three dots to end! It is flatter, outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara steps across to block. The ball rolls out off the pads. Clearly outside the line.
Goes full, around off, turning away. Pujara smothers it to point.
Much fuller, on off. Puraja steps down and blocks it back to the bowler.
Looped up, on leg. Kohli gets forward and closes the face of the bat to work it past mid on. They cross. 50 up for India and the crowd gets loud here.
Quicker and full, angled across. Kohli presses forward and dabs it down.
Murphy comes from 'round the wicket. He strays on the pads. Kohli rocks back and flicks it through square leg for two runs.
Floated and full, on middle. Pujara defends it out solidly.
Full and on off. Cheteshwar Pujara blocks it on his front foot.

FOUR! Cheteshwar Pujara means business in this post-Lunch session. He gets out of his bubble and uses his feet to attack here. It is full and on leg. Pujara steps down and lofts it over mid on. A couple of bounces over the ropes.
Full and on off, defended out.
Fatter and outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara gets across and pads it away.
It is full, angled across the right-hander. Virat Kohli uses his bottom hand and drills it down to long on. One taken.
Delivers this one slightly short and outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara goes on the back foot and pushes this towards cover.
Angles this into the pads on a fuller length. Cheteshwar Pujara blocks this towards sshort leg.
Loopy delivery bowled full and just outside off. Virat Kohli gets a good stride forward and knocks this towards long off for a run.
Fires this one full and into the stumps. Virat Kohli goes deep in the crease and dabs this inro the leg side.
Tosses this one full and in line with the stumps. Cheteshwar Pujara uses his feet and clips this towards deep mid-wicket for one.
Matthew Kuhnemann floats this one full and outside off. Virat Kohli uses his bottom hand and whips this towards wide long on for one.
Fires this into the pads on a fuller length. Cheteshwar Pujara flicks this towards short fine leg and a maiden over from Nathan Lyon.
Flatter and on leg. Pujara uses his feet and flicks it to mid-wicket.
Flights this full and into the stump. Cheteshwar Pujara shuffles forward and defends it into the leg side.

Nathan Lyon flights this one full and outside off, gets it to keep its line and beats the outside edge. Alex Carey whips this bails off in a flash and they go upstairs to check for a stumping. Cheteshwar Pujara did not leave his crease.
Tosses this one full and outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara gets forward to push at the ball and gets it down to short leg.
Dot now! Nathan Lyon serves it full and on leg. Cheteshwar Pujara nudges it to short leg.
A dot to end a successful over! It is full and on off, turning away a touch. Kohli presses forward and blocks it into the deck.
Virat Kohli comes in at number 4.

OUT! RUN OUT! Absolute chaos and Rohit Sharma has sacrificed his wicket here! Matthew Kuhnemann floats this one full and into the stumps, Rohit Sharma flicks this towards deep square leg and they run the first one quick. Rohit Sharma calls for the second and Cheteshwar Pujara responds but Peter Handscomb is quick to attack the ball in the deep. He collects it and throws it at the keeper's end and Rohit Sharma asks Cheteshwar Pujara to go back but he is already darting to the non-striker's end. Rohit Sharma stays out of the crease and begins to walk back to the shed as Alex Carey whips the bails off. India lose their second wicket and they will still believe.

SIX! Commanding batting from Rohit Sharma and he is showing some great footwork here! Matthew Kuhnemann tosses this full and in line with the stumps. Rohit Sharma is down the wicket in a flash and thumps this back over the bowler's head for a six.
Fires this one full and outside the off stump, Rohit Sharma gets his front foot forward and dabs this into the off side.
Bowls this short and outside off, Cheteshwar Pujara rocks back and punches this towards deep point for one.
Marnus Labuschagne floats this one full and outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara shimmies down once again and knocks this to cover.
Loopy delivery bowled full and in line with the stumps. Rohit Sharma gets forward and looks to dab it down the pitch but gets hit on the pad. The bowler appeals but the umpire remains unmoved.

FOUR! Rohit Sharma is playing on the bowler's mind! Nathan Lyon bowls this slightly short and going down leg. Rohit Sharma makes the initial movement to come forward but ends up sitting in the crease and paddles this fine for four runs.
Goes full and spins this into the pads. Cheteshwar Pujara also shuffles forward and clips this towards deep square leg for one.
Flights this one full and outside off. Rohit Sharma uses his feet again and knocks this down to long on for one.

SIX! That is a massive hit! Nathan Lyon tosses this full and outside the off stump. Rohit Sharma charges down the wicket and lofts this over long on for a maximum. He did not time it well but had enough on it to clear the fence.
Nathan Lyon bowls this slightly short and on a leg stump line. Rohit Sharma shimmies down the wicket and looks to block but gets hit n the pads.
It will be Nathan Lyon to spin from the other end.
Another flighted delivery bowled full and outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara bunts this back to the bowler.
Loopy delivery going doing leg on a fuller length. Cheteshwar Pujara pushes forward and gets hit on the pads.
Tosses this one full and outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara dabs this back towards the bowler.
FOUR! That races away to the fence! Matthew Kuhnemann flights this full and in line with the stump. Cheteshwar Pujara flicks this towards deep mid-wicket for four runs.
Flights this full and outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara dabs this into the leg side.

We are back for the second session of what should be the last day of this game. The umpires are out in the middle and the Australian players take their respective positions on the field. Rohit Sharma and Cheteshwar Pujara will be looking to take India through this tricky period and set up the run chase. Matthew Kuhnemann will begin proceedings after Lunch. Let's go...
Matthew Kuhnemann floats this one full and into the pads. Rohit Sharma clips this towards mid-wicket and gets a run right away.
... DAY 3, SESSION 2 ...

Chasing a target of 115, KL Rahul was dismissed in an unfortunate manner but Rohit Sharma has batted positively. Cheteshwar Pujara is a nervous starter but you can bank on his experience to navigate the Indian innings on a surface favourable for the spinners. They are 101 runs away at the moment. Do join us at 12.10 pm IST (6.40 am GMT) for the afternoon session.

End of an action-packed morning session! 10 wickets fell in total and it's India on top. Australia were abysmal with their batting approach and got bundled out cheaply by the spin pair of Ashwin and Jadeja who bagged his best bowling figures in an inning of a Test match. This match is travelling with the speed of light and the hosts will be delighted to put themselves in a position to win this game.
Two dots on the trot to end the over. Nathan Lyon now comes over the wicket. It is tossed up, outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara rushes off the crease and pads it away. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 3.
Flatter and on leg stump. Cheteshwar Pujara hangs back and clips it past short leg. A slight miscommunication but no trouble.
This is darted on the pads, Rohit Sharma stays back and clips it through square leg. One taken.
Cheteshwar Pujara gets off the mark now! It is a half-tracker, on leg. Cheteshwar Pujara swivels and pulls it to deep square leg for one.
Cheteshwar Pujara gets forward and blocks this full one back to the bowler.
Loopy ball, on the pads. Cheteshwar Pujara nudges it square on the leg side. Pujara ventures out looking for a single but the skipper sends him back. He stays on zero.

FOUR! Clinical placement. Rohit Sharma bisects the two fielders in the deep. It is full, on middle and leg. Rohit Sharma leans across and flicks it powerfully along the ground. It meets the boundary at deep mid-wicket.
This is angled in full and into the pads. Rohit Sharma tucks it to short leg.
Floats it up, outside off, it grips and turns away sharply. Rohit Sharma is happy with a sighter as he leaves.
Full and around off, Rohit strides forward and blocks it to the off side.
Floated and on middle, Sharma takes a step down the track and wrists it through mid-wicket for two runs.
Loopy and full, around off, Rohit presses forward and defends.
Floats it up, on middle and leg. Pujara nudges it past short leg.
Cheteshwar Pujara now comes down the track and clips it to mid-wicket.
Lyon goes full and on leg. Pujara stays back and flicks it to the right of short leg.
This is a bit quicker, on middle and leg. It turns back in to hit Pujara on the pads.

NOT OUT! Cheteshwar Pujara is safe! Lyon tosses it up, outside off. Cheteshwar Pujara presses forward and tries to block it away but misses as the ball skids away a touch. Alex Carey collects and takes the bails off. The square-leg umpire takes it upstairs. It is confirmed that Pujara's back leg is well grounded.
Appeal for stumping...
Cheteshwar Pujara walks in next. After getting out for a duck, he will like to first get off the mark in his 100th Test.

OUT! CAUGHT! KL Rahul shakes his head as he walks off the field here. A bit of fortune for Australia, for the first time this morning. Nathan Lyon strikes on his very first delivery. The spinner comes from 'round the wicket. Floats it up, on leg, KL Rahul rocks back and clips it to short leg. Peter Handscomb stays low there and the ball rebounds off his right leg. It loops up to the keeper and Alex Carey takes the catch off the deflection. Rahul's poor form in Test cricket continues.
Commentary.Howout: c Alex Carey b Nathan Lyon

Commentary.Commentary: Who will bowl from the opposite end? It is Nathan Lyon.

FOUR! Hit with fire. It is full and on off. Rohit Sharma steps down and drills it past the bowler's right. Matthew Kuhnemann dives to his right but gets no hand on it. The ball is over the fence at long on in a flash. India are off to a solid start.
Matthew Kuhnemann tosses it up, outside off. KL Rahul drives it through the line towards sweeper cover. He gets off the mark with a single here.
Flights it up, full and wide of off, turns away a touch. KL Rahul just watches it sail past him.
Rohit Sharma and India are off the mark! It is full and on off. Rohit Sharma prods and gets it to covers off the outer half. The Indian skipper is quick to get to the other end.
Dot again! Much straighter this time, full, on off. Sharma stays back and strokes it to covers.
